        <h1>
          Article 32: Remedies for enforcement of rights conferred by this Part
        </h1>
        <p>
          * The right to move the Supreme Court by appropriate proceedings for
          the enforcement of the rights conferred by this Part is guaranteed.
        </p>
        <p>
          * The Supreme Court shall have power to issue directions or orders or
          writs, including writs in the nature of habeas corpus, mandamus,
          prohibition, quo warranto and certiorari, whichever may be
          appropriate, for the enforcement of any of the rights conferred by
          this Part.
        </p>
        <p>
          * t acts as a safeguard for fundamental rights by allowing individuals
          to seek direct judicial intervention from the highest court in the
          country.
        </p>
        <p>
          * In Simple Words: Article 32 ensures that if someone fundamental
          rights are violated, they can approach the Supreme Court to get
          justice and enforce those rights.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="ar20">
      <div class="container">
        <h1>
          Article 32A: Constitutional validity of State laws not to be
          considered in proceedings under article 32
        </h1>
        <p>
          * Article 32A was added to the Indian Constitution by the 44th
          Amendment Act of 1978. It relates to the power of the Supreme Court to
          enforce fundamental rights and specifies certain conditions under
          which it can review laws affecting such rights.
        </p>
        <p>
          * Article 32A allows the Supreme Court to examine whether any law
          passed by Parliament or a state legislature is in conflict with
          fundamental rights
        </p>
        <p>
          * This article also ensures that the Supreme Court’s power to review
          laws is not affected by any limitations imposed by earlier laws or
          amendments.
        </p>
        <p>
          * In summary, Article 32A strengthens the Supreme Court’s role in
          safeguarding fundamental rights by allowing it to review and ensure
          laws comply with constitutional protections.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="seccontainer">
