          Article 35: Legislation to give effect to the provisions of this Part
        </h1>
        <p>
          * Article 35 of the Indian Constitution deals with the power of
          Parliament to make laws for enforcing fundamental rights and the
          protection of such laws from being challenged in court.
        </p>
        <p>
          * Article 35 gives Parliament the authority to make laws to enforce
          the fundamental rights guaranteed by the Constitution. This ensures
          that these rights are effectively implemented and protected.
        </p>
        <p>
          * Laws made under Article 35 cannot be challenged in court solely on
          the grounds that they infringe on fundamental rights. This helps
          protect the legislative measures taken to uphold these rights.
        </p>
        <p>
          * In simple terms, Article 35 allows Parliament to make and protect
          laws necessary for implementing fundamental rights, ensuring that
          these laws cannot be easily challenged in court.
        </p>
      </div>
